ce:section.ce:para:
Batch adsorption experiments were carried out to determine the adsorption efficiency of polymers. For batch studies, 10 mg of PIP-FCDs or PNIP-FCDs were suspended in 50 mL (100 mL Erlenmeyer flask) of IBF solution. The solution was stirred at 200 rpm for 30 min using a magnetic stirrer to reach the adsorption equilibrium. Afterwards, the PIP-FCDs were separated by centrifugation at 8000 rpm for 10 min, and the supernatant solution was collected. The concentration of free IBF in supernatant solution was measured by UV–Vis spectrophotometer at 264 nm. The influence of key controlling parameters (e.g., initial concentration of IBF, contact time of IBF with PIP-FCDs, adsorbent dose, initial pH of the solution, and temperature) on the absorption was investigated and optimized. By examining the absorption of IBF from solution at different time peroids, adsorption kinetics was studied. Adsorption isotherms were determined by varying the initial IBF concentrations between 10 and 80 mg L−1. Adsorption thermodynamics was investigated at 25, 35, and 45 °C. The adsorption performance was assessed for removal efficiency (RE (%)) and adsorption capacity (qt (mg g−1)) (see entries i and ii in Table S3). To ensure the accuracy of the experimental findings, every experiment was carried out in triplicate. The results of repeated measurements revealed relative standard deviation (< 5 %). Isotherm models (Langmuir and Freundlich models) and kinetic models (pseudo-first-order (PFO), pseudo-second-order (PSO), and intraparticle diffusion (IPD) models were applied to: i) illustrate the interactions among the adsorbate and adsorbent, ii) evaluate the efficacy of the adsorbent, and iii) comprehend the process of adsorption dynamics. The experimental data was fitted to non-linear forms of isotherm and kinetic approaches to reduce the bias stemming from linearized approaches. The equations applied for the isotherm and kinetic models based on non-linear approaches are listed in Table S3 (see entries iii – viii). A non-linear model was fitted to the experiment data. The analysis of the non-linear curve fitting involved using custom-defined functions within the Origin software, with an initial parameter set to one in the user-defined equation. The coefficient of determination (R2) and Chi-square (
χ 2
) (Eq. (2)) were considered as the factors for kinetic and isotherm model suitability (see entries viii and ix in Table S3). Additionally, thermodynamic parameters such as the standard entropy change (ΔS°), enthalpy change (ΔH°), and free energy change (ΔG°) were calculated using expressions mentioned in Table S3 (see entries x – xii) to investigate the thermodynamic behavior. The imprinting factors (IF), distribution coefficient (Kd, L g−1), selectivity coefficient (α), and relative selectivity coefficient (β) were calculated (using equations as entries xiii – xvi in Table S3) to learn more about the selectivity of the PIP-FCDs and PNIP-FCDs.

Adsorption studies using PIP-FCDs as a sorbent have been effectively utilized to extract target IBF from wastewater, tap water, and pharmaceutical tablet samples. The following experimental parameters (Fig. 4 (a – d)) were seen to yield the optimum RE%: (a) initial concentration;
C o
= 30 mg L−1 of IBF, (b) contact time of 30 min., (c) adsorbent dosage of 10 mg per 50 mL, and (d) adsorption temperature of 25 °C. In-depth information on how to optimize the PIP-FCDs as a sorbent for its extraction applications is provided in the supplementary information Text S1. The pH of the solution is crucial to the adsorption process because it disturbs the ionization of analytes in the solution as well as the surface charge of the adsorbent. Adsorption studies were performed in the pH range of 3–11 to completely comprehend the impact of pH. As can be seen from Fig. 4e, IBF removal by PIP-FCDs was not significantly altered by solution pH (pH = 6–8). However, in the highly acidic (pH 3–5) and basic medium (9–11), RE% was decreased, which could be attributed to the loss of active sites of PIP-FCDs. The protonation of imprinted cavities was responsible for the reduced responsiveness seen at a lower pH. With this modification, there was less hydrogen bonding between IBF and the PIP-FCDs probe. Additionally, when hydrogen ions are in solution under acidic conditions, the strength of hydrogen bonding can be decreased. In addition, at pH <6, most of the IBF is presented in the molecular form (pKa = 5.2) and PDA layer in PIP-FCDs existed in cationic form [39]. Due to this, the H-bonding gets weakened between the PIP-FCDs and IBF, causing less adsorption. On the other hand, at high pH (> 8), the anionic IBF generates repulsion with the PDA layer. This prevents the analyte from penetrating the binding sites, which results in a reduction in adsorption. Similarly, the zeta potential of PIP-FCDs material was investigated at various pH values, and the results displayed that, at pH 7, the zeta potential for PIP-FCDs was −35.2 mV (standard deviation = 4.8 mV). Because the electronegative donor atoms (N, O) were present and it was not altered significantly at a higher pH of 9 (−23.3 mV; standard deviation = 2.7 mV) but at pH 3, a low negative value (i.e., −16.7 mV; standard deviation = 0.9 mV) was detected due to protonation of PIP-FCDs (Fig. 4f). Likewise, results were observed from pH-dependent adsorption studies. Thus, based on these findings, subsequent experiments were conducted under neutral conditions (pH = 7).
